SCANSNAP

          A simple command-line tool that talks to Fujitsu ScanSnap
     iX500 scanners over WiFi. Put paper in, run the command, get a
     PDF. No daemon, no GUI, no dependencies beyond libc and pthreads.

          May also work with other ScanSnap models that use WiFi
     (iX1500, etc.) — reports welcome.


BUILD

          make

DOCKER

          Build:

              docker build -t scansnap .

          Show help:

              docker run --rm scansnap

          Scan to the current directory using a saved key:

              docker run --rm \
                -v "$PWD:/work" \
                -v "$HOME/.config:/config" \
                scansnap -s SCANNER_IP

          Notes:

          - The container includes the `ip` command because the tool
            uses `ip route get` internally to pick the correct
            interface.
          - Auto-discovery works best with host networking. On Linux,
            use `--network host`. On Docker Desktop, passing `-s IP`
            is usually the safer option.
          - `--getkey` needs the ScanSnap Home app to reach the fake
            scanner ports. That generally means `--network host`, or
            equivalent host-network support in your Docker runtime.

QUICK START WITH DOCKER ON LINUX

          On Linux, run the container with host networking so the
     scanner sees the real host IP and MAC address:

              mkdir -p output config/scansnap
              printf 'YOUR_PAIRING_KEY\n' > config/scansnap/key
              chmod 600 config/scansnap/key

              docker build -t scansnap .
              docker run --rm \
                --network host \
                -v "$PWD/output:/work" \
                -v "$PWD/config:/config" \
                scansnap -d -s SCANNER_IP -o /work/scan.pdf

          Scanned files are written to `./output` on the host. Keep
     ScanSnap Home stopped while using the container.

DOCKER COMPOSE WORKFLOW

          The compose setup is meant for a Linux host on the same LAN
     as the scanner. It persists two directories in the repository:

          - `./output` for scanned PDFs/JPEGs
          - `./config` for the saved pairing key

          Prepare the folders and build once:

              mkdir -p output config
              docker compose build

          One-time pairing key bootstrap:

          1. Turn off or disconnect the real scanner
          2. Start the fake scanner:

                 docker compose run --rm scansnap --getkey

          3. Open ScanSnap Home on your Mac or Windows machine
          4. Wait for the key to be printed and saved to:

                 ./config/scansnap/key

          Regular scans with the saved key:

              docker compose run --rm scansnap -s SCANNER_IP

          The PDF is written to `./output` because `/work` is bound to
     that folder inside the container. If you already know the pairing
     key, you can skip the bootstrap step and either put it in
     `./config/scansnap/key` or pass `-k KEY` manually.

          Stop ScanSnap Home before regular scans. Its background
     helpers keep registering with the scanner and can hold the device
     in a busy session state, which shows up as handshake error -4.

          Important:

          - The compose file uses `network_mode: host` because the
            protocol setup needs the scanner to see the host IP and,
            for `--getkey`, to reach ports 52217, 53218 and 53219.
          - This is reliable on Linux. Docker Desktop on macOS/Windows
            can still build the image, but runtime communication with
            the physical scanner may fail because host networking is
            not equivalent there.
          - For custom output names, append normal CLI flags:

                docker compose run --rm scansnap -s SCANNER_IP -o /work/my_scan.pdf
          - If `--getkey` sees no traffic on a multi-homed host, run
            it in debug mode and force the advertised host IP:

                docker compose run --rm scansnap -d --getkey --getkey-ip HOST_LAN_IP
          - If ScanSnap Home keeps sending UDP registrations but never
            opens TCP 53219, match the fake scanner identity more
            closely to the real device:

                docker compose run --rm scansnap \
                  -d --getkey \
                  --getkey-ip HOST_LAN_IP \
                  --getkey-name 'iX500-XXXXXXXXXX' \
                  --getkey-model 'ScanSnap iX500' \
                  --getkey-mac 'SCANNER_MAC' \
                  --getkey-tail 'TAIL_HEX_FROM_CAPTURE'
          - For firmware-specific debugging, dump the live TCP `0x11`
            handshake request/response and patch individual bytes:

                ./scansnap -d -s SCANNER_IP -k KEY \
                  --dump-handshake handshake.log \
                  --handshake-patch OFFSET:HEX_BYTES

          - Compare the first TCP `0x11` request across captures:

                python3 scripts/compare_handshakes.py try-to-get-key.pcapng try-to-get-key4.pcapng


SETUP (one time)

          Your scanner is paired with a key — the serial number of
     its internal WiFi module. If the scanner was set up with the
     official ScanSnap Home app, that app knows the key, so we
     trick it into telling us:

     1. Turn off or disconnect the real scanner
     2. Run "scansnap --getkey" (needs ports 52217, 53218, 53219 —
        may need sudo)
     3. Open ScanSnap Home on your Mac or Windows machine — it will
        find the fake scanner and send the key
     The key is saved to ~/.config/scansnap/key automatically.
     You only need to do this once.


SCAN

          scansnap

          The scanner is found automatically on your local network.
     Pages come out as a timestamped PDF in the current directory.

          If ScanSnap Home is installed on the same machine, quit it
     completely before scanning. On macOS the menu bar app leaves helper
     processes running; stop them before using this tool:

          pkill -f '/Applications/ScanSnapHomeMain.app'

          Error -4 means the scanner still has a busy/stale session.
     Turn the scanner off and on, make sure ScanSnap Home is not
     running, then retry.


KNOWN LIMITATIONS

          This v0.1 release supports active scans: the command starts
     the scan and writes PDF/JPEG output. A physical scanner-button
     daemon mode is not implemented yet.

          The scanner only supports one active client session. If
     ScanSnap Home or one of its background helpers is running, the
     scanner may reject this tool with error -4. Stop ScanSnap Home
     and restart the scanner if the stale session does not clear.

          Docker Desktop networking on macOS/Windows is not equivalent
     to Linux host networking. For reliable scanner access, run the
     container on a Linux host in the same LAN as the scanner.


SECURITY AND PRIVACY

          Treat the pairing key as a secret. It authorizes a client to
     talk to the scanner.

          Packet captures and debug handshake logs can contain pairing
     keys, MAC addresses, IP addresses and scanned image data. Do not
     publish them.


BUTTON DAEMON ROADMAP

          The current captures suggest that ScanSnap Home keeps or
     prepares a scanner session and then scans from that state when the
     physical scanner button is pressed. They do not prove a simple
     scanner-initiated callback that a passive client can wait for.

          A future daemon mode should own the scanner session, keep
     ScanSnap Home stopped, monitor scanner state, and write timestamped
     PDFs when a button-triggered scan is detected. See
     `docs/button-daemon-roadmap.md` for the proposed follow-up spec.


OPTIONS

     -s IP       scanner IP (skip auto-discovery)
     -k KEY      pairing key from setup step
     -o FILE     output filename (default: scan_YYYYMMDD_HHMM.pdf)
     -j          save as separate JPEG files instead of PDF
     -1          single-sided (discard back pages)
     -d          debug output
     --getkey    capture pairing key (see setup)
     --getkey-ip IP
                 advertise this host IP in fake scanner mode
     --getkey-name NAME
                 fake scanner device name for `--getkey`
     --getkey-model MODEL
                 fake scanner model string for `--getkey`
     --getkey-mac MAC
                 fake scanner MAC for `--getkey`
     --getkey-tail HEX
                 8-byte hex tail for the UDP device info response
     --client-ip IP
                 override local client IP for scanner communication
     --client-mac MAC
                 override client MAC for scanner communication
     --dump-handshake FILE
                 append TCP 0x11 request/response hex to FILE
     --handshake-patch OFFSET:HEX
                 patch bytes in the TCP 0x11 request before sending


HOW IT WORKS

          The scanner speaks a proprietary protocol ("VENS") over
     UDP and TCP. See the PROTOCOL file for the full reverse-
     engineered specification.


